actual.value:
A gap exists within the transition from school to work. Chott Mariem's teachers do not have sufficient knowledge on climate smart agriculture, modern greenhouse management including irrigation, fertigation and climate control, on greenhouse establishment, and on entrepreneurship, which are priority themes in the agricultural sector. Consequently, the staff are not able to teach the students on these topics, which causes a gap between the competencies of TVET graduates and the needs within the agricultural sector. Moreover, the Tunisian education system lacks interactive teaching techniques, soft skills, and coaching, which enlarges the gap between graduated students and the job market. By training the staff on above mentioned topics, this programme contributed to bridging the knowledge gap of the staff.

The main lessons learned are:

1. Mixing theory, practice, online and on-site training creates a dynamic training;
2. Having a demonstration cultivation in the greenhouse fosters experimental learning;
3. Providing online cultivation advice in between on-site training weeks is very useful to keep production going and the participants motivated;
4. Combining trainers from multiple TVETs causes a bigger difference in backgrounds but is very good for creating connections.

It is recommended to implement a follow-up training programme to update and extend the gained theory and skills. The focus should be on:

1. Production of other crops (for instance tomato or pepper, which are the main crops in greenhouse vegetable production and also important on the Tunisian market);
2. Extending the knowledge gained on entrepreneurship, for instance by giving the participants their own demonstration greenhouse for one cultivation cycle. They will receive some money to start cultivation and are expected to return it after the cultivation cycle. They will have to buy inputs for cultivation (seeds, substrate etc), manage cultivation (crop work, coordinating labour), marketing and selling their produce, and lastly managing their inputs and outputs by making a business plan.

Moreover, it is recommended to continue stimulating collaboration and knowledge sharing between the TVETs, for instance by hosting demonstration days and visiting each other’s demonstration greenhouses and open fields.
